>they look "amateurish" to me
That'd be because you're symbol drawing, i.e. putting down contours in shapes symbolic of the thing you're trying to depict, with little understanding of how that thing is really constructed. This is a common rookie artist mistake; trying to stylize reality before you've built an understanding of how reality actually looks. This is the reason art teachers tell you to just stop copying anime (but for some dumbfuck reason rarely elaborate as to why and leave their students scratching their heads and likely spiteful enough to deliberately ignore the advice); all you learn doing that is how to copy one very specific way to stylize, as opposed to learning constructing with basic shapes in perspective and refining the finer details with the aid of references, which allows you to depict basically anything you could ever want to with minimal adapting.

I'd recommend drawabox.com's later lessons (the construct-a-bug ones especially are an effective crash course) to get started on the basics of these fundamentals, i.e. skip the draw-a-shitload-of-boxes part of the equation, since you're likely already familiar enough with linework to not need the extra muscle memory exercise.
